# Binaries for programs and plugins
# Compiled executables for the main application and any tools.
*.exe
*.dll
*.so
*.dylib
*.o
*.a

# Test binaries
# Executables generated when running tests.
*.test
*.out

# Generated by Go toolchain
#
# Ignore all 'bin/' directories. This is where compiled binaries often reside.
# If you have specific binaries you *do* want to commit, you'll need to
# add exceptions (e.g., `!/bin/my_tool`).
bin/

# Ignore all 'pkg/' directories. This contains cached build artifacts and
# should not be committed to version control.
pkg/

# Dependency directories (vendoring)
#
# If you use `go mod vendor` to create a local copy of dependencies,
# this directory will be created. It's generally not committed to
# version control as `go mod download` handles dependencies.
vendor/

# Environment variables
#
# This file contains sensitive information (e.g., API keys, database credentials)
# and should never be committed to version control.
# A `.env.example` is provided for reference.
.env

# Log files
#
# Ignore any log files generated by the server.
logs/
*.log

# Temporary files
#
# Ignore any temporary files or directories created during runtime or development.
tmp/
*.tmp

# IDE and editor specific files
#
# VS Code specific settings and user preferences.
.vscode/

# IntelliJ IDEA specific settings and project files.
.idea/

# macOS specific files
#
# Files created by macOS for custom folder icons and metadata.
.DS_Store

# Editor backup files
#
# Common backup files created by various text editors (e.g., Emacs, Vim).
*~
.#*
*.swp
*.swo

# Other potential build artifacts or caches
#
# If frontend assets were built into a 'dist' or 'build' directory,
# those would be ignored here. For this project, 'web/static' contains
# source files, so it should be committed.
# For example:
# web/static/dist/
# web/static/build/